ce:section.ce:para:
Application of the PNCQDs/Cr(VI) probe for AA sensing in various kinds of food samples was investigated further. The recoveries of this method were determined by spiking a series of different known concentrations of AA. As shown in Table 1
                     , the AA contents in the fresh fruits, such as orange, red grape and kiwi, detected by the fabricated “off-on” probe, were 30.80, 5.12 and 58.75 mg/100 g, respectively. Meanwhile, the AA content was also determined in the commercial fruit juices (Table 2
                     ), such as orange juice, peach juice and sea-buckthorns juice; the results were 9.37, 5.8 and 17.73 mg/100 g, respectively. It is worth to note that the quantitative spike recoveries for the detection of AA in these above real samples ranged from 95% to 105%, with a relative standard deviation of less than 4.2% (n = 5). These results further demonstrated that the PNCQDs/Cr(VI) probe for monitoring AA in practical food samples was reliable and feasible.
